  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improved lifesaving trauma care services in high risk regions</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project is in line with SO1 and SO3 of 2018-2021 Afghanistan Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP). Additional the Health context 11, and 12 of 6 Reserves Allocation strategy highlights the need for improved trauma care services as it mentions that the number of trauma cases reported nationwide increased by 14% (Report Hub, 2018). And the trauma facilities are overstretched, and occupancy rates are routinely over 200% (Emergency, 2018 and HMIS, 2018). And armed conflict in western and southern regions have high number of civilian casualties and moreover, there have been some damage to the health facilities. Lack of trauma care in drought affect areas is widespread.&quot;
Afghanistan continues to face immense humanitarian, social and political challenges. The current drought affected 9.8 million people in 21 out of 34 provinces are in humanitarian assistance, including almost 500,000 who are in urgent needs of essential and emergency health services (Health Cluster assessment, October 2018). The ongoing insecurity and recent drought is causing displacement among communities across Herat and Badghis. . Baghis, Faryab, Uruzgan are particularly affected by active conflict which add to the burden of drought on the existing overstretched health system. As consequence of the ongoing conflict, there is an urgent need for life saving and trauma care medical services as per the increasing in the number of trauma cases  over the last year nationally. The number of trauma cases reported nationwide has increased by 14% (Report Hub, 2018). 
This project includes activities to improve the trauma care and life-saving medical services by upgrading the provincial, district and one of the Comprehensive Health Centers in the priority provinces of drought and ongoing conflicts, with trauma care services and blood bank. In addition,  the project will focuse on improvement of the emergency response capacities in those provinces. Moreover, there will support to improve coordination both at national and sub-national levels. The beneficiaries will include the  patients will come to health facilities from the drought affected IDPs, host communities and other IDPs or returnees.
The direct beneficiaries will be a mix of host communities, IDPs, returnees and from nearby areas affected by war. The dis-aggregated data is not available, that is why other is selected to report all of the beneficaries of the project.</narrative>
  </description>
